snippet.textDisplay:
I was lazily assuming that all bottled water, even mineral or spring water, went through reverse osmosis or other processes that essentially rendered them identical before having different mineral quantities added back in, but this video inspired me to actually go and check. Natural mineral and spring water can't actually have RO done to it, or much of anything other than filtration or some adsorption to lower fluoride content (at least in the UK).

Even so..."it's all just water" :-) Extraordinary health claims go on being nonsense regardless of my lazy assumptions.

One of the most irritating trends I've seen is the sale of "ultra-pure" water, in third world nations especially where consumers may be less aware, and often it's sold as a premium brand. This water has gone through RO or other techniques to make it potable, but had no minerals added back in afterward. It's not adding anything to your diet and costs more than better alternatives. I recall the WHO and other authorities used to recommend not drinking it at all, according to MSDS from chemistry labs I've worked in, though I'm not sure it would really do much harm if you also eat food (as is the usual way of humans), and drink other water.

Use to run a Dasani filling machine about a decade ago. My 12 hour shift pumped enough water out of the local resevoir to fill a tractor trailer every 15 minutes with cases of water. About 340,000 bottles in a 12 hour shift. If I remember right, there was one more line like mine and a new 500,000 bottle line they'd just put in.

The new production line bumped the cost per case of water up from ten cents to fifty while it paid for itself.

snippet.textDisplay:
Tom, I've known this since the year 2000. As a Trucker, I was told to go pick up a full load of this bottled water at the Coca Cola bottling building in Washington, PA. USA
When there, I was Surprised to learn that it was only bottling Pittsburg PA Tap Water that was filtered and enhanced.
My Second Surprise was Seeing it sold at McDonalds Fast Food places all over the USA and Canada.
I always felt like people who bought that Bottled tap water were unaware of it's Origin. Thank You for this informative Video. Hopefully the word will spread out.
